Specify Test Rules with cypress-axe

04
On this page
  1. An Overview of the cypress-axe Extension
  2. Add Accessibility API Tests to the MegaNav Spec
  3. 🛠 Challenge: Configure cypress-axe to Only Check Color Contrast Issues
  4. 🛠 Solution: Update the cypress-axe Usage
  5. A Note on When to Use Which Testing Tool
  6. Wrapping up Cypress Component Testing

We’ve written tests that check the behavior of our components.

Now we’ll write tests that check our components against accessibility rules using a testing API.

An Overview of the cypress-axe Extension

Cypress offers a large selection of extensions that bring in additional functionality.

Of particular interest to us is the cypress-axe plugin.

This plugin brings the accessibility testing functionality of axe-core into Cypress, allowing us to write tests that take advantage of its rules. We also get similar test results through automation as we would using the Axe browser extension.

Similar to how we we configured cypress-real-events, to enable the plugin we import it inside of cypress/support/commands.js:

import "cypress-axe";
import "cypress-axe";

You can learn more about cypress-axe on the plugin’s GitHub page and browse more Cypress plugins in their docs.

Add Accessibility API Tests to the MegaNav Spec

Let’s write a test that checks the color contrast of the MegaNav component using the axe-core API.

The first step to using the cypress-axe plugin is to inject it into our test’s beforeEach:

describe('MegaNav'), () => {
	beforeEach(() => {
		mount(<MegaNav/>)

		cy.injectAxe()
	})
})
describe('MegaNav'), () => {
	beforeEach(() => {
		mount(<MegaNav/>)

		cy.injectAxe()
	})
})

Create a new it statement for a test and give it a name related to checking accessibility issues:

it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
	
})
it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
	
})

In order for cypress-axe to check for issues, you need to get the component under test into the proper state first. This is because axe-core only checks what it can find on load of a component or page.

For testing the MegaNav, this means that we need Cypress to open the menu for us. To save time, copy the cy.get() from another test that will click one of the MegaNav’s buttons.

With the menu open, we then call cy.checkA11y() to check for issues in the browser and assert there are none:

it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
        cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').click()

        cy.checkA11y()
  })
it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
        cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').click()

        cy.checkA11y()
  })

Now when we run Cypress, we find that our accessibility test fails!

The test fails because cypress-axe is set up to check an entire page by default.

So when it looks at the MegaNav component, it doesn’t find an H1 or a main landmark because these would be present elsewhere on the page.

With a bit of configuration, cypress-axe can be told to only check for specific rules or element selectors. See the full API on the axe-core GitHub repo, including the context parameter and additional options.

🛠 Challenge: Configure cypress-axe to Only Check Color Contrast Issues

In order to make this test pass with cypress-axe, we need to do some configuration to tell it what rule(s) to look for.

Referencing the example usage in the cypress-axe README and the axe-core rules, update the test to only look for color contrast issues.

🛠 Solution: Update the cypress-axe Usage

In the README on the cypress-axe GitHub page, there’s an example of supplying a runOnly option to cy.checkA11y():

// from cypress-axe's README
cy.checkA11y('.example-class', {
	runOnly: {
		type: 'tag',
		values: ['wcag2a']
	}
})
// from cypress-axe's README
cy.checkA11y('.example-class', {
	runOnly: {
		type: 'tag',
		values: ['wcag2a']
	}
})

Building on this example, we can replace the .example-class with null because we want Cypress to check everything. We also swap out tag with rule since we are interested in using a specific rule.

Referencing the rule list in the axe-core docs, it ends up that the rule related to color contrast has been conveniently named color-contrast.

Putting this together, our test now looks like this:

it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
  cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').click()

  cy.checkA11y(null, {
    runOnly: {
    type: 'rule',
    values: ['color-contrast']
   }
 })
})
it('should have no accessibility issues when open', () => {
  cy.get('button[data-testid="megamenu-section1"]').click()

  cy.checkA11y(null, {
    runOnly: {
    type: 'rule',
    values: ['color-contrast']
   }
 })
})

Running the test, we now see that it passes as expected.

A Note on When to Use Which Testing Tool

As a full test suite with Cypress Component Testing, cypress-axe looks for issues that don’t necessarily apply.

As we’ve seen, there are several different tools built on axe-core that are available as plugins to IDEs, browser extensions, and in Storybook.

While it is nice to be able to find these types of accessibility issues in an automated manner, they really should be caught earlier in the development process. Better late than never, though!

In a production application for a client, I might not use cypress-axe at the component level this way in favor of running it in the scope of the full application when using Cypress Integration Testing as we will see in the next module. This would come after manual testing to catch any automated issues that slipped through the cracks.

Wrapping up Cypress Component Testing

As we’ve seen with Storybook and Jest, it’s useful to interact with and test our components in isolation with Cypress Component Testing

Cypress Component Testing’s tooling and API make it a great tool for testing, particularly if you plan on using Cypress for integration testing at the application level.

You’ll get some practice with it in the next section!
